A '''raincheck''' is an informal agreement by a [[merchant]] to a [[customer]] to provide an item the merchant has run out of at a later date for the item's current price, or (in a more literal sense) to provide a service at a later date which cannot currently be provided due to rain or other inclement weather.  The former is particularly useful if the merchant was having a [[sale]] on the item, as the customer can return later and use the rain check to purchase the item at the sale price even if the item is no longer on sale.

The term may have originated in the era of open-air [[market]]s where the occurrence of significant [[rain]] usually required a vendor to pack up his goods and leave. Others argue that the origin of the term comes from American baseball - early stadiums were often roofless, and in the event of rain the stadium managers would distribute raincheck slips which allowed ticket holders to watch the game at a later date without purchasing an additional ticket.



